ter of Michael Sars, wife of Fridtjof Nansen \n* [[Georg Ossian Sars]] (1837\u20131927), Norwegian biologist, son of Michael Sars\n* [[Maren Sars]] (1811\u20131898) n\u00e9e Welhaven, Norwegian socialite and wife of Michael Sars\n* [[Michael Sars]] (1805\u20131869), Norwegian biologist and priest\n* [[Sarah D. Bunting]] or Sars, a founder of the television recap site Television Without Pity\n\n==Other uses==\n* [[Sarsfield's GAA (disambiguation)]], several sports clubs whose name is often abbreviated Sars\n* [[SARS (band)]] (Sve\u017ee Amputirana Ruka Satrijanija), a Serbian alternative rock band\n\n==See also==\n{{canned search|sars}}\n* [[SAR (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Sarsaparilla (soft drink)]] or sarsi\n* {{lookfrom|SARS}}\n* {{lookfrom|Sars}}\n* {{intitle|sars}}\n\n{{Disambiguation|surname}}\n", "text_old": "{{Wiktionary|SARS|s\u00e5rs}}\n'''[[SARS]]''' is severe acute respiratory syndrome, a viral respiratory disease identified in the early 2000s caused by the SARS coronavirus.\n\n'''SARS''' or '''Sars''' may also refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n==Biology and medicine==\n* ''[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus]]'' (''SARSr-CoV'' or ''SARS-CoV''), a virus species containing:<!--despite all these technically being [[WP:PTM]] - keep these here-->\n** [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus]] (SARS-CoV or SARS-CoV-1), a strain that causes SARS\n** [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2), a strain that causes:\n*** [[Coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), an infectious disease first identified in 2019\n** [[Bat SARS-like coronavirus WIV1]] (Bat SL-CoV-WIV1 or SARS-like coronavirus WIV1), a strain isolated from Chinese rufous horseshoe bats<!--this one could arguably be moved to the See also, but included as the third strain of the species-->\n* [[SARS (gene)|''SARS'' (gene)]], a human gene for encoding the enzyme cytoplasmic seryl-tRNA synthetase\n\n==Places==\n* [[Sars (urban-type settlement)]], a settlement in Perm Kra