{"title_page": "John Plummer Marcellus", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image =\n| imagesize = |\n| name = John Plummer Marcellus\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1838|7|26}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1932|5|29|1838|7|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Morrisburg, Ontario]]\n| death_place = [[Pincher Creek, Alberta]]\n| residence = \n| office = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|Member of the Legislative Assembly of Alberta]]\n| constituency = [[Pincher Creek (provincial electoral district)|Pincher Creek]]\n| term_start = 1905\n| term_end = 1909\n|alongside = \n| predecessor = \n| successor =[[David Warnock]]\n| party = Liberal\n| religion =\n| spouse=\n| occupation = rancher, farmer\n}}\n'''John Plummer Marcellus''' (July 26, 1838 \u2013 May 29, 1932) was a politician and rancher from [[Alberta]], Canada.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born at [[Morrisburg, Ontario]]. Marcellus married his wife Maria Barkley in 1871 at [[Dunbar, Ontario]].\n\n==1905 election==\nMarcellus ran for the Alberta legislature in the [[1905 Alberta general election]]. He won a hotly contested 3-way race in the Pincher Creek electoral district in rural southeast Alberta. He served one term as a backbencher in the Legislative Assembly before retiring in 1909. He died in 1932 at [[Pincher Creek]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pioneersalberta.org/profiles/m.html#marcellus_j John P. Marcellus Pioneer Profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101026192825/http://www.assembly.ab.ca/legislaturecentennial/pdf/membersBooklet.pdf Legislative Assembly of Alberta Members Listing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcellus, John}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alberta Liberal Party MLAs]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| image =\n| imagesize = |\n| name = John Plummer Marcellus\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1838|7|26}}\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1932|5|29|1838|7|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Morrisburg, Ontario]]\n| death_place = [[Pincher Creek, Alberta]]\n| residence = \n| office = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|Member of the Legislative Assembly of Alberta]]\n| constituency = [[Pincher Creek (provincial electoral district)|Pincher Creek]]\n| term_start = 1905\n| term_end = 1909\n|alongside = \n| predecessor = \n| successor =[[David Warnock]]\n| party = Liberal\n| religion =\n| spouse=\n| occupation = rancher, farmer\n}}\n'''John Plummer Marcellus''' (July 26, 1838 \u2013 May 29, 1932) was a politician and rancher from [[Alberta]], Canada.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born at [[Morrisburg, Ontario]]. Marcellus married his wife Maria Barkley in 1871 at [[Dunbar, Ontario]].\n\n==1905 election==\nMarcellus ran for the Alberta legislature in the [[1905 Alberta general election]]. He won a hotly contested 3 way race in the Pincher Creek electoral district in rural southeast Alberta. He served one term as a backbencher in the Legislative Assembly before retiring in 1909. He died in 1932 at [[Pincher Creek]].\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pioneersalberta.org/profiles/m.html#marcellus_j John P. Marcellus Pioneer Profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101026192825/http://www.assembly.ab.ca/legislaturecentennial/pdf/membersBooklet.pdf Legislative Assembly of Alberta Members Listing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marcellus, John}}\n[[Category:1838 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alberta Liberal Party MLAs]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1905 election:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 3 way \u2192 3-way", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Plummer_Marcellus"}
{"title_page": "Kaycee Madu", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Kaycee Madu\n| birth_date ={{Birth based on age as of date|45|2019|4|10}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Paige Parsons |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/riding-profile-edmonton-south-west |title=Alberta Election 2019 riding profile: Edmonton-South West |publisher=Edmonton Journal |date=2019-04-10 |accessdate=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n| birth_place =[[Nigeria]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|MLA]]\n| smallimage = \n| caption =\n| office = [[List of Alberta provincial ministers#Minister of Municipal Affairs|Minister of Municipal Affairs of Alberta]]\n| predecessor = [[Shaye Anderson]]\n| premier = [[Jason Kenney]]\n| term_start = April 30, 2019\n| office1 = Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] for [[Edmonton-South West]]\n| succeeding=\n| term_start1 = April 16, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor1 =\n| successor = \n| party =[[United Conservative Party]]\n| occupation = lawyer\n| residence= [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]]\n| alma_mater=\n}}\n'''Kaycee (Kelechi) Madu''' is a Canadian politician who was elected in the [[2019 Alberta general election]] to the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] representing the [[electoral district]] of [[Edmonton-South West]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Derek Van Diest Updated: April 16, 2019 |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/results-kacyee-madu-wins-edmonton-south-west-in-tightly-contested-battleground |title=Results: Kacyee Madu wins Edmonton-South West in tightly contested battleground |publisher=Edmonton Journal |date= |accessdate=2019-04-17}}</ref> On 30 April 2019, Madu was appointed to the [[Executive Council of Alberta]] as the Minister of Municipal Affairs.\n\nOn March 4, 2020, Kaycee Madu was designated as a Queen's Counsel by the Lieutenant Governor of Alberta via an Order-in-Council. Queen's Counsel is the highest honour awarded to lawyers who have made significant contributions to the advancement of law and society. \n\n<!--- ==Electoral history==\n===2019 general election=== --->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=Jason_Kenney}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post1preceded = [[Shaye Anderson]]\n| post1         = [[Executive Council of Alberta|Minister of Municipal Affairs]]\n| post1years    = April 30, 2019&ndash;\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = [[Incumbent]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Alberta MLAs}}\n{{Kenney Ministry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madu, Kaycee}}\n[[Category:United Conservative Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of Alberta]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Kaycee Madu\n| birth_date ={{Birth based on age as of date|45|2019|4|10}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Paige Parsons |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/riding-profile-edmonton-south-west |title=Alberta Election 2019 riding profile: Edmonton-South West |publisher=Edmonton Journal |date=2019-04-10 |accessdate=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n| birth_place =[[Nigeria]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|MLA]]\n| smallimage = \n| caption =\n| office = [[List of Alberta provincial ministers#Minister of Municipal Affairs|Minister of Municipal Affairs of Alberta]]\n| predecessor = [[Shaye Anderson]]\n| premier = [[Jason Kenney]]\n| term_start = April 30, 2019\n| office1 = Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] for [[Edmonton-South West]]\n| succeeding=\n| term_start1 = April 16, 2019\n| term_end = \n| predecessor1 =\n| successor = \n| party =[[United Conservative Party]]\n| occupation = lawyer\n| residence= [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]]\n| alma_mater=\n}}\n'''Kaycee (Kelechi) Madu''' is a Canadian politician who was elected in the [[2019 Alberta general election]] to the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] representing the [[electoral district]] of [[Edmonton-South West]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Derek Van Diest Updated: April 16, 2019 |url=https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/results-kacyee-madu-wins-edmonton-south-west-in-tightly-contested-battleground |title=Results: Kacyee Madu wins Edmonton-South West in tightly contested battleground |publisher=Edmonton Journal |date= |accessdate=2019-04-17}}</ref> On 30 April 2019, Madu was appointed to the [[Executive Council of Alberta]] as the Minister of Municipal Affairs.\n\nOn March 4, 2020, Kaycee Madu was designated as a Queen\u2019s Counsel by the Lieutenant Governor of Alberta via an Order-in-Council. Queen\u2019s Counsel is the highest honour awarded to lawyers who have made significant contributions to the advancement of law and society. \n\n<!--- ==Electoral history==\n===2019 general election=== --->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{Canadian cabinet member navigational box header |ministry=Jason_Kenney}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post1preceded = [[Shaye Anderson]]\n| post1         = [[Executive Council of Alberta|Minister of Municipal Affairs]]\n| post1years    = April 30, 2019&ndash;\n| post1note     =\n| post1followed = [[Incumbent]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Alberta MLAs}}\n{{Kenney Ministry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Madu, Kaycee}}\n[[Category:United Conservative Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Executive Council of Alberta]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaycee_Madu"}
{"title_page": "Hugh MacDonald (politician)", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2009}}\n{{One source|date=June 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox politician\n| image =  Hugh-MacDonald-2007(250).jpg|\n| name = Hugh MacDonald\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|8|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Souris, Prince Edward Island|Souris]], [[Prince Edward Island]], Canada\n| residence = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| office = [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|MLA]] for [[Edmonton-Gold Bar]]\n| term_start = March 11, 1997\n| term_end = April 23, 2012\n| predecessor = [[Bettie Hewes]]\n| successor = [[David Dorward]]\n| party = [[Alberta Liberal Party|Liberal]]\n| religion =\n| occupation = business owner\n}}\n\n'''Hugh MacDonald''' (born August 5, 1955<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.albertaliberal.com/index.php/alp/caucus_member |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102183050/http://www.albertaliberal.com/index.php/alp/caucus_member/ |archive-date=2014-01-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who represented the [[electoral district (Canada)|electoral district]] of [[Edmonton-Gold Bar]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]]. He is a member of the [[Alberta Liberal Party]]. On September 27, 2011, he announced he would not seek re-election.\n\n==Background==\nBorn August 5, 1955, he spent 20 years working in Alberta's petroleum industry as a boilermaker and small business owner prior to becoming an MLA.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230700/http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMacDonald was first elected as a Member of the Alberta Legislature in the general election of 1997. He was elected to his second term for Edmonton-Gold Bar on March 12, 2001, his third on November 22, 2004, and, most recently, to his fourth term on March 3, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230700/http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition, MacDonald was the critic for Advanced Education and Technology, Employment and Immigration and Infrastructure.\n\nMacDonald served as chair of the Public Accounts Committee and as a member of the following committees:\n\nAlberta Heritage Savings Trust Fund\nLegislative Offices Committee\nPrivate Bills Committee\nStanding Committee on Public Safety and Services\nSelect Special Chief Electoral Officer Search Committee<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230700/http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe has served as chair of the Standing Committee on Public Accounts and as a member of the Select Special Ethics Commissioner Search Committee and the Personal Information Protection Act Review Committee. MacDonald has also served as the Official Opposition critic for Agriculture, Food and Rural Development, Energy, the Heritage Savings Trust Fund, Human Resources and Employment and Government Services.\n\nAdditionally, he has served as a member of the standing committees on Law and Regulations and Privileges and Elections, Standing Orders and Printing. MacDonald has assumed Official Opposition critic positions including:\n\nCritic responsible for Employment and Immigration\nCritic responsible for Infrastructure<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://alc.whitematter.ca/index.php/alc/caucus_member/hugh_macdonald/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007204319/http://alc.whitematter.ca/index.php/alc/caucus_member/hugh_macdonald/ |archive-date=2009-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Rally4HealthcareHugh.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Hugh MacDonald|Liberal MLA Hugh MacDonald]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=mla_bio&rnumber=32 Profile at the Legislative Assembly of Alberta]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macdonald, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Alberta Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Boilermakers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kings County, Prince Edward Island]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2009}}\n{{One source|date=June 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox politician\n| image =  Hugh-MacDonald-2007(250).jpg|\n| name = Hugh MacDonald\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|8|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Souris, Prince Edward Island|Souris]], [[Prince Edward Island]], Canada\n| residence = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| office = [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta|MLA]] for [[Edmonton-Gold Bar]]\n| term_start = March 11, 1997\n| term_end = April 23, 2012\n| predecessor = [[Bettie Hewes]]\n| successor = [[David Dorward]]\n| party = [[Alberta Liberal Party|Liberal]]\n| religion =\n| occupation = business owner\n}}\n\n'''Hugh MacDonald''' (born August 5, 1955<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.albertaliberal.com/index.php/alp/caucus_member |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102183050/http://www.albertaliberal.com/index.php/alp/caucus_member/ |archive-date=2014-01-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, who represented the [[electoral district (Canada)|electoral district]] of [[Edmonton-Gold Bar]] in the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]]. He is a member of the [[Alberta Liberal Party]]. On September 27, 2011, he announced he would not seek re-election.\n\n==Background==\nBorn August 5, 1955, he spent 20 years working in Alberta\u2019s petroleum industry as a boilermaker and small business owner prior to becoming an MLA.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230700/http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMacDonald was first elected as a Member of the Alberta Legislature in the general election of 1997. He was elected to his second term for Edmonton-Gold Bar on March 12, 2001, his third on November 22, 2004, and, most recently, to his fourth term on March 3, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230700/http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition, MacDonald was the critic for Advanced Education and Technology, Employment and Immigration and Infrastructure.\n\nMacDonald served as chair of the Public Accounts Committee and as a member of the following committees:\n\nAlberta Heritage Savings Trust Fund\nLegislative Offices Committee\nPrivate Bills Committee\nStanding Committee on Public Safety and Services\nSelect Special Chief Electoral Officer Search Committee<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712230700/http://www.hughmacdonald.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58 |archive-date=2011-07-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHe has served as chair of the Standing Committee on Public Accounts and as a member of the Select Special Ethics Commissioner Search Committee and the Personal Information Protection Act Review Committee. MacDonald has also served as the Official Opposition critic for Agriculture, Food and Rural Development, Energy, the Heritage Savings Trust Fund, Human Resources and Employment and Government Services.\n\nAdditionally, he has served as a member of the standing committees on Law and Regulations and Privileges and Elections, Standing Orders and Printing. MacDonald has assumed Official Opposition critic positions including:\n\nCritic responsible for Employment and Immigration\nCritic responsible for Infrastructure<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://alc.whitematter.ca/index.php/alc/caucus_member/hugh_macdonald/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-01-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007204319/http://alc.whitematter.ca/index.php/alc/caucus_member/hugh_macdonald/ |archive-date=2009-10-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Rally4HealthcareHugh.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Hugh MacDonald|Liberal MLA Hugh MacDonald]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.assembly.ab.ca/net/index.aspx?p=mla_bio&rnumber=32 Profile at the Legislative Assembly of Alberta]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macdonald, Hugh}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Alberta Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Boilermakers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kings County, Prince Edward Island]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_MacDonald_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Mark Hlady", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| name                = Mark Hlady\n| honorific-suffix    =\n| image= Mark Hlady.jpg\n| imagesize=200px\n| caption = Mark Hlady standing on the Calgary Peace Bridge in his home riding of Calgary-Mountain View in 2018\n| office              = Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] for [[Calgary Mountain View]]\n| term_start          = June 15, 1993\n| term_end            = November 22, 2004\n| predecessor         =[[Bob Hawkesworth]]\n| successor           = [[David Swann]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1959|3|4}}\n| birth_place         = [[Fort William, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         = \n| party               =[[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]]\n| otherparty          = \n| children            =\n| occupation          = \n}}\n'''Mark Everett Hlady''' (born March 4, 1959) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] businessman and politician and a former member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]].<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=cOSIAAAAMAAJ&q=\"Hlady,+mark\"+1959&dq=\"Hlady,+mark\"+1959&hl=en&sa=X&ei=p8g7VZiKDMy0ggTLl4KwAw&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA]</ref>\n\nHlady was elected in the [[1993 Alberta general election|1993 general election]] as a [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta|Progressive Conservative]] in the riding of [[Calgary-Mountain View]], defeating [[Alberta New Democratic Party|New Democrat]] [[Bob Hawkesworth]]. Hlady kept his seat in the [[1997 Alberta general election|1997]] and [[2001 Alberta general election|2001]] elections, but was defeated in [[2004 Alberta general election|2004]] by [[Alberta Liberal Party|Liberal]] contender [[David Swann]]. During his term as an MLA, Hlady served on many oil and gas related committees.\n\nHe is currently seeking the 2018 United Conservative Party nomination in the Calgary-Mountain View riding.\n\n==Background==\nHlady was born in [[Fort William, Ontario|Fort William]], [[Ontario]]. In 1979 he moved to [[Calgary]] to work for the family home improvement business and has lived there ever since. He was educated at the [[University of Calgary]] and graduated with a Physical Education degree in 1990.\n\nSince Hlady graduated, he completed the Canadian Securities Course and became a stockbroker. Hlady earned his Real Estate License in 2016 and is currently a Remax Real Estate Central agent.\n\nHe is currently the Head Coach of the University of Calgary Triathlon club which he founded in 1986.\n\n==Political career==\n\nIn the fall of 1992, he was asked to work on [[Ralph Klein]]\u2019s leadership campaign. After Klein won the leadership race, Hlady was encouraged to run in Calgary-Mountain View against incumbent [[Bob Hawkesworth]]. During what is now known as \"the miracle on the prairies\", the party overcame a significant gap in popular support, behind the opposition [[Alberta Liberal Party]], to win the 1993 election. As an MLA, Hlady helped secure funding and supported initiatives such as the building of the Bow Valley Seniors Lodge, Wing Kei Care Centre, Soccer Fields in Renfrew and school playgrounds across the constituency.\n\nHlady was one of the youngest MLAs in Alberta's history.\n\nHe ran as the party's candidate in the same district in the [[2015 Alberta general election|2015 provincial election]], but was not reelected.\n\nHlady is currently seeking the 2018 United Conservative Party nomination in the Calgary-Mountain View constituency.\n\n{{Alberta provincial election, 2015/Calgary-Mountain View}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hlady, Mark}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Thunder Bay]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta MLAs]]\n[[Category:University of Calgary alumni]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n\n\n{{Alberta-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| name                = Mark Hlady\n| honorific-suffix    =\n| image= Mark Hlady.jpg\n| imagesize=200px\n| caption = Mark Hlady standing on the Calgary Peace Bridge in his home riding of Calgary-Mountain View in 2018\n| office              = Member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]] for [[Calgary Mountain View]]\n| term_start          = June 15, 1993\n| term_end            = November 22, 2004\n| predecessor         =[[Bob Hawkesworth]]\n| successor           = [[David Swann]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1959|3|4}}\n| birth_place         = [[Fort William, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         = \n| party               =[[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta]]\n| otherparty          = \n| children            =\n| occupation          = \n}}\n'''Mark Everett Hlady''' (born March 4, 1959) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] businessman and politician and a former member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Alberta]].<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=cOSIAAAAMAAJ&q=\"Hlady,+mark\"+1959&dq=\"Hlady,+mark\"+1959&hl=en&sa=X&ei=p8g7VZiKDMy0ggTLl4KwAw&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA]</ref>\n\nHlady was elected in the [[1993 Alberta general election|1993 general election]] as a [[Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta|Progressive Conservative]] in the riding of [[Calgary-Mountain View]], defeating [[Alberta New Democratic Party|New Democrat]] [[Bob Hawkesworth]]. Hlady kept his seat in the [[1997 Alberta general election|1997]] and [[2001 Alberta general election|2001]] elections, but was defeated in [[2004 Alberta general election|2004]] by [[Alberta Liberal Party|Liberal]] contender [[David Swann]]. During his term as an MLA, Hlady served on many oil and gas related committees.\n\nHe is currently seeking the 2018 United Conservative Party nomination in the Calgary-Mountain View riding.\n\n==Background==\nHlady was born in [[Fort William, Ontario|Fort William]], [[Ontario]]. In 1979 he moved to [[Calgary]] to work for the family home improvement business and has lived there ever since. He was educated at the [[University of Calgary]] and graduated with a Physical Education degree in 1990.\n\nSince Hlady graduated, he completed the Canadian Securities Course and became a stockbroker. Hlady earned his Real Estate License in 2016 and is currently a Remax Real Estate Central agent.\n\nHe is currently the Head Coach of the University of Calgary Triathlon club which he founded in 1986.\n\n==Political career==\n\nIn the fall of 1992, he was asked to work on [[Ralph Klein]]\u2019s leadership campaign. After Klein won the leadership race, Hlady was encouraged to run in Calgary-Mountain View against incumbent [[Bob Hawkesworth]]. During what is now known as \"the miracle on the prairies\", the party overcame a significant gap in popular support, behind the opposition [[Alberta Liberal Party]], to win the 1993 election. As an MLA, Hlady helped secure funding and supported initiatives such as the building of the Bow Valley Seniors Lodge, Wing Kei Care Centre, Soccer Fields in Renfrew and school playgrounds across the constituency.\n\nHlady was one of the youngest MLAs in Alberta\u2019s history.\n\nHe ran as the party's candidate in the same district in the [[2015 Alberta general election|2015 provincial election]], but was not reelected.\n\nHlady is currently seeking the 2018 United Conservative Party nomination in the Calgary-Mountain View constituency.\n\n{{Alberta provincial election, 2015/Calgary-Mountain View}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hlady, Mark}}\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Thunder Bay]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Calgary]]\n[[Category:Progressive Conservative Association of Alberta MLAs]]\n[[Category:University of Calgary alumni]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n\n